1 Overview
**********

This is a simple package that renders an indicator with an email count
of the ‚Äònotmuch‚Äô index on the Emacs mode line.  The underlying mechanism
is that of ‚Äònotmuch-count(1)‚Äô, which is used to find the number of items
that match the given search terms.

   The indicator is displayed when ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-mode‚Äô is enabled.

   The user option ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-args‚Äô provides the means to define
search terms and associate them with a given label.  The label is a
purely cosmetic string to helps describe or differentiate the resulting
counter.  For example, the letter "U" or the emoji "üí¨" can accompany
search terms for "unread items".  The resulting indicator may optionally
be styled with a face, only for the label, only for the counter, or
both.

   Concretely, the value of ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-args‚Äô is a list of plists
(property lists).  Examples are shown further below.

   Each plist consists of one mandarory property and three optional
ones:

  1. The ‚Äò:terms‚Äô, which is required, is a string that holds the
     command-line arguments passed to ‚Äònotmuch-count(1)‚Äô (read the
     Notmuch documentation for the technicalities).

  2. The ‚Äò:label‚Äô, which is optional, is an arbitrary string that is
     prepended to the return value of the above.  If the value is nil or
     the property is omitted, no label is displayed.

  3. The ‚Äò:label-face‚Äô, which is optional, is the symbol of a face that
     is applied to the ‚Äò:label‚Äô.  It should not be quoted, so like :face
     bold.  Good candidates are ‚Äòbold‚Äô, ‚Äòitalic‚Äô, ‚Äòsuccess‚Äô, ‚Äòwarning‚Äô,
     ‚Äòerror‚Äô, though anything will do.  If the value is nil or the
     property is omitted, no face is used.  For backward-compatibility,
     ‚Äò:face‚Äô has the same meaning as ‚Äò:label-face‚Äô.

  4. The ‚Äò:counter-face‚Äô, which is optional, is like ‚Äò:label-face‚Äô but
     applies to the number of the given counter.  It accepts the
     unquoted symbol of a face, as noted above, though it also takes a
     ‚Äòinherit‚Äô value which means to use the same face as the
     ‚Äò:label-face‚Äô.  This too is an unquoted symbol.  If the value is
     nil, or the property is omitted altogether, the counter does not
     have a face assigned to it.

   Multiple plist lists represent separate ‚Äònotmuch-count(1)‚Äô queries.
These are run sequentially.  Their return values are joined into a list
of strings.  By default, this is shown on the mode line, wherever
‚Äòmode-line-misc-info‚Äô is displayed.  Refer to the user option
‚Äònotmuch-indicator-add-to-mode-line-misc-info‚Äô to control the placement
of the ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-mode-line-construct‚Äô.

   For instance, a value like the following defines three searches (in
the source code the quotes are escaped--please check the Help buffer for
the clean code (I dislike markup in doc strings)):

     (setq notmuch-indicator-args
          '((:terms "tag:unread and tag:inbox" :label "@")
             (:terms "from:bank and tag:bills and tag:unpaid" :label "üò±")
             (:terms "--output threads tag:fans" :label "‚ù§Ô∏è")))

   These form a list of strings which appears as something like this:
‚Äò@2 üò±1000 ‚ù§Ô∏è0‚Äô (sorry, the ‚Äònotmuch-indicator‚Äô is no miracle worker:
your fan mail will not be more than your unpaid bills).

   Same idea as above, but with faces applied:

     (setq notmuch-indicator-args
          '(( :terms "tag:unread and tag:inbox"
              :label "@"
              :label-face success)
            ( :terms "from:bank and tag:bills and tag:unpaid"
              :label "üò±"
              :counter-face warning)
            ( :terms "--output threads tag:fans"
              :label "‚ù§Ô∏è"
              :label-face error
              :counter-face inherit)))

   Each counter is clickable: it runs ‚Äònotmuch-search‚Äô on the applicable
‚Äò:terms‚Äô., assuming the ‚Äònotmuch.el‚Äô is set up.  In other words,
clicking on the counter produces a Notmuch buffer with the given search
terms.

   The user option ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-refresh-count‚Äô determines how
often the indicator is refreshed.  It accepts a numeric argument
representing seconds.

   The user option ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-force-refresh-commands‚Äô accepts as
its value a list of symbols.  Those are commands that will forcefully
update the indicator after they are invoked.

   The user option ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-hide-empty-counters‚Äô hides zero
counters from the indicator, when it is set to a non-nil value.

   The user option ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-notmuch-config-file‚Äô specifies the
file system path to the local user's Notmuch configuration file.

   The file is one among:

   ‚Ä¢ ‚Äò$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/notmuch/$NOTMUCH_PROFILE/config‚Äô
   ‚Ä¢ ‚Äò$HOME/.notmuch-config.$NOTMUCH_PROFILE‚Äô
   ‚Ä¢ ‚Äò$HOME/.notmuch-config‚Äô

   See the function ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-get-config-file‚Äô for how we
return the right path.  The user can set this user option to an
arbitrary path if the aforementioned function does not return the
desired value.

   We store this the first time ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-mode‚Äô is loaded so
that the indicator can still show the data of the local user even when
they are browsing a remote file system with TRAMP.  Alternatively, the
user may wish to have different indicators depending on the TRAMP
environment, in which case the value of this user option must be updated
accordingly (DEV NOTE: please contact me if you have such a use-case, as
I am happy to make the package more flexible).

   The user option ‚Äònotmuch-indicator-notmuch-binary‚Äô specifies the file
system path to the ‚Äònotmuch‚Äô binary.  Concretely, this is the return
value of ‚Äò(executable-find "notmuch")‚Äô.


